Dear Emis,

Org A has connected your Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with you. The team's name is Team AZ.

Why has this happened?
Team AZ holds information about you or for you. PKB links you to the team so you can see information about you (such as test results) and information for you (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging).

Your PKB record is a single place to store information from you, your health professionals and your medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website.

What happens next?
When you have registered, if Team AZ sends you information, PKB will notify you by email.

What if I do not know the Org A or Team AZ team?
Sometimes you may see an organisation or team name that is unfamiliar to you. This often happens when health care services share resources for managing their patients' or service users' care. How do I know what information they have about me and what they can see about me?

This team is able to see information in your record marked with general privacy. This team is not able to see information marked with social, mental and sexual privacy.

You can change the level of access they have at any time by clicking this link and adjusting their settings, you can read more in the PKB manual.

Dear Emis,

Org A has connected Emis's Patients Know Best (PKB) record to a new team that is, or has been, working with them. The team's name is Team AZ.

Why has this happened?
Team AZ holds information about or for Emis. PKB links them to the team so you can see information about them (such as test results) and information for them (such as library links). In some cases, you can interact with the team (through secure messaging).

Their PKB record is a single place to store information from you, Emis, their health professionals and their medical devices. To learn more about PKB, please visit our website.

What happens next?
When you have registered, if Team AZ sends Emis information, PKB will notify you by email. If Emis has registered, they will receive an email too.

What if I do not know the Org A or Team AZ team?
Sometimes you may see an organisation or team name that is unfamiliar to you. This often happens when health care services share resources for managing their patients' or service users' care. For example, GPs and hospitals sometimes share laboratory systems for test results, and therefore one can receive data from an organisation without having been there.

How do I know what information they have about Emis and what they can see in the record?
The information the team has about or for Emis so far is in their PKB record. You can log in to see it now.

This team is able to see information in their record marked with general privacy. This team is not able to see information marked with social, mental and sexual privacy.

You can change the level of access they have at any time by clicking this link and adjusting their settings, you can read more in the PKB manual.

You are receiving this notification because you are a carer. To log in and review the people you care for, please click this link: "http://pkb-frontend-10/patient/myDependents.action?tab=invitations&subTab=dependents"

Please do not reply to this email; this address is not monitored. Log into your record to manage your care and those whom you care for.

Yours,

Patients Know Best Help Team
